    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">And here is a kind of cheat sheet:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*vZiLuozj4LI7i895.jpg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">3. Matrix-Matrix Addition and Subtraction</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Matrix-Matrix Addition and Subtraction is fairly easy and straightforward. The requirement is that the matrices have the same dimensions and the result is a Matrix that has also the same dimensions. You just add or subtract each value of the first Matrix with its corresponding value in the second Matrix. See below:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*IUd6HEGLynRK83PP.jpg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">4. Matrix-Matrix Multiplication</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Multiplying two Matrices together isn’t that hard either if you know how to multiply a Matrix by a Vector. Note that you can only multiply Matrices together if the number of the first Matrix’s columns matches the number of the second Matrix’s rows. The result will be a Matrix with the same number of rows as the first Matrix and the same number of columns as the second Matrix. It works as follows:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">You simply split the second Matrix into column-Vectors and multiply the first Matrix separately by each of these Vectors. Then you put the results in a new Matrix (<em>without</em> adding them up!). The image below explains this step by step:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*6dIH-o3Ee9-j9ZCP.jpg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">And here is again some kind of cheat sheet:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*qGwQsRHW_jnq5BwJ.jpg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Matrix Multiplication Properties</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Matrix Multiplication has several properties that allow us to bundle a lot of computation into one Matrix multiplication. We will discuss them one by one below. We will start by explaining these concepts with Scalars and then with Matrices because this will give you a better understanding of the process.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">1. Not Commutative</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Scalar Multiplication is commutative but Matrix Multiplication is not. This means that when we are multiplying Scalars, 7*3 is the same as 3*7. But when we multiply Matrices by each other, A*B isn’t the same as B*A.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">2. Associative</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Scalar and Matrix Multiplication are both associative. This means that the Scalar multiplication 3(5*3) is the same as (3*5)3 and that the Matrix multiplication A(B*C) is the same as (A*B)C.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">3. Distributive</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Scalar and Matrix Multiplication are also both distributive. This means that <br></br>3(5 + 3) is the same as 3*5 + 3*3 and that A(B+C) is the same as A*B + A*C.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">4. Identity Matrix</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The Identity Matrix is a special kind of Matrix but first, we need to define what an Identity is. The number 1 is an Identity because everything you multiply with 1 is equal to itself. Therefore every Matrix that is multiplied by an Identity Matrix is equal to itself. For example, Matrix A times its Identity-Matrix is equal to A.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">You can spot an Identity Matrix by the fact that it has ones along its diagonals and that every other value is zero. It is also a “squared matrix,” meaning that its number of rows matches its number of columns.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*shATGElNK0aXQoij.jpg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We previously discussed that Matrix multiplication is not commutative but there is one exception, namely if we multiply a Matrix by an Identity Matrix. Therefore, the following equation is true: <strong>A*I = I*A = A</strong></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Inverse and Transpose</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The Matrix inverse and the Matrix transpose are two special kinds of Matrix properties. Again, we will start by discussing how these properties relate to real numbers and then how they relate to Matrices.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">1. Inverse</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">First of all, what is an inverse? A number that is multiplied by its inverse is equal to 1. Note that every number except 0 has an inverse. If you multiply a Matrix by its inverse, the result is its Identity Matrix. The example below shows what the inverse of Scalars looks like:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*MgI9VqKnOFQr5wkc.jpg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">But not every Matrix has an inverse. You can compute the inverse of a Matrix if it is a “squared Matrix” and if it has an inverse. Discussing which Matrices have an inverse would be unfortunately out of the scope of this post.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><mark>Why do we need an inverse? Because we can’t divide Matrices. There is no concept of dividing by a Matrix but we can multiply a Matrix by an inverse, which results essentially in the same thing.</mark></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The image below shows a Matrix multiplied by its inverse, which results in a 2-by-2 identity Matrix.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*fsy33tEPMWzRFXzo.jpg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">You can easily compute the inverse of a Matrix (if it has one) using Numpy. Heres the link to the documentation: <a href="https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.14.0/reference/generated/numpy.linalg.inv.html" target="_self">https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.14.0/reference/generated/numpy.linalg.inv.html</a>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">2. Transpose</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">And lastly, we will discuss the Matrix Transpose Property. This is basically the mirror image of a Matrix, along a 45-degree axis. It is fairly simple to get the Transpose of a Matrix. Its first column is the first row of the Matrix Transpose and the second column is the second row of the Matrix Transpose. An m*n Matrix is transformed into an n*m Matrix. Also, the Aij element of A is equal to the Aji(transpose) element. The image below illustrates that:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*iyQK2Gpo_1vX7hMU.jpg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Summary</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In this post, you learned about the mathematical objects of Linear Algebra that are used in Machine Learning. You learned how to multiply, divide, add and subtract these mathematical objects. Furthermore, you have learned about the most important properties of Matrices and why they enable us to make more efficient computations. On top of that, you have learned what inverse and transpose Matrices are and what you can do with them. Although there are also other parts of Linear Algebra used in Machine Learning, this post gave you a proper introduction to the most important concepts.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
